moves.prompt:
Your name is agent_1. Public environment information:
{environment->public_information}
Your private information:
{agents->agent_1->private_information}
Global goal:
{agents->agent_1->goal}
Produce a complete, ordered list of primitive moves for the disks you are allowed to move. Use the exact move format 'agent_1: move disk X from peg1 to peg2'. Think step by step and ensure move legality. If some moves depend on agent_2, produce your moves that you can perform consistently without making assumptions about unspecified private information of the other agent.

Your name is agent_2. Public environment information:
{environment->public_information}
Your private information:
{agents->agent_2->private_information}
Global goal:
{agents->agent_2->goal}
Produce a complete, ordered list of primitive moves for the disks you are allowed to move. Use the exact move format 'agent_2: move disk X from peg1 to peg2'. Think step by step and ensure move legality. If some moves depend on agent_1, produce your moves that you can perform consistently without making assumptions about unspecified private information of the other agent.

pddl.prompt:
You are orchestrator. Global goal:
{agents->orchestrator->goal}
You will receive the move lists from the two agents:
{moves_agent_1}
{moves_agent_2}
1) Validate and integrate the lists into a single, consistent sequence of primitive moves that respects the Tower of Hanoi rules and agent permissions.
2) Produce a PDDL domain and problem pair that models the environment, agents, disks, pegs, and the integrated sequence as either constraints or an initial/goal specification suitable for FastDownwards. Distinguish agent-specific actions in the domain so that actions by agent_1 and agent_2 remain separate and enforce that only the permitted agent can perform moves on each disk.
Enclose the PDDL domain between <domain></domain> tags, and the PDDL problem between <problem></problem> tags.
